			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					WoW lead dev: We killed MMO genre
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1786126">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							His saying that wow killed a genre is a little bit strongly worded but the fact is mmos as a genre are not at all where they started and that's fine for the casual gamer that considers all the changes he listed as improvements, but now there are not many options for the people who want all the things he listed to be the way they were. <br />
<br />
His post there was obviously meant to appeal to those people, and they are probably the minority but they're still out there and there's no reason why they can't have games that cater to the hardcore. Warcraft (and the other more recent mmos) don't have an endgame solution that appeals to the elitists. <br />
<br />
My play time varies from week to week in wow but sometimes when I have a free lazy weekend I get frustrated by the fact there's not much I can do to advance my character in any way meaningful to me. Their answer to that is making it easier to level up an alt or giving me Pokemon minigames, which I don't like. <br />
<br />
I guess be insulted if you want, or you could admit that the entire mmo genre in much more casual today than it was at its roots and realize that not every game that comes out has to be optimized to fit your schedule when there are others with desire and ability to spend far more time playing than you can and they want some tangible result for doing so.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
