		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: WoW lead dev: We killed MMO genre
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1786146">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Naean</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">His saying that wow killed a genre is a little bit strongly worded but the fact is mmos as a genre are not at all where they started and that's fine for the casual gamer that considers all the changes he listed as improvements, but now there are not many options for the people who want all the things he listed to be the way they were.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>There's plenty of games with high difficulty. Heroic raiding in WoW for individual skill, EVE Online for group organization skill, hell, you could go back to Everquest if you like. What doesn't exist is a massively popular game that is high in difficulty, and it should be obvious why that is the case. The point at which I realized this fellow had a massive axe to grind was here:<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Article</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">We created a massive number of quests to lead the player through the world, making sure that they never had to think about what to do next.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Vanilla WoW may have had quests to send people to all the corners of the world, but it also had a lot of cryptic quests and hidden quests. It wasn't all &quot;collect ten bear asses&quot; like it is today. It also sent people to all the corners of the world so those places would be used and experienced. I know a lot of developers want to massively reward explorers, to make exploration this high risk (lost time when there's nothing there, chance of failure) high reward activity. WoW chose to make exploration low risk and low reward, to make seeing all the corners of the world the new normal. As a former EQ player, I respect that decision to make sure players see everything a developer placed in game.<br />
<br />
Another thing that strikes me from his article is how he equates length of an XP curve with difficulty. Needing more XP doesn't make the game more difficult. It makes the game more time-consuming. You're not taxing the player's ability to come up with solutions to the difficult problems they encounter in game, you're seeing how much free time they have to play the game.<br />
<br />
Finally, there's one thing in his article that really outs what type of player he is:<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Article</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">And you don&#8217;t feel satisfied from playing the game because it never challenged you.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>He's an achiever. He wants to do things that have some kind of lasting respect, things he can point to and say, &quot;I did that, and it proves I have some value as a player.&quot; But the Bartle Test has three other types of player in it, and the things he describes don't seem to have a lot of value for them.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Dawlin</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">I still consider the post a marketing ploy to get a hold of the people who already have decided that &quot;lulz wow is too easy, I need a challenging game!&quot;. All while having not a single heroic raid kill under their belt.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>On. The. Nose. &quot;I don't play that BABY game, I play a TOUGH game!&quot; Ok, tough guy, have &quot;fun&quot; with that.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
